item.description:
Statisticians classically asked the wrong question — and were willing to answer with a lie, one that was often a downright lie. They asked &ldquo;Are the effects of A and B different?&rdquo; and they were willing to answer &ldquo;no.&rdquo;
All we know about the world teaches us that the effects of A and B are always difference — in some decimal place — for any A and B. Thus asking &ldquo;Are the effects different?&rdquo; is foolish.
What we should be answering first is &ldquo;Can we tell the direction in which the effects of A differ from the effects of B?&rdquo; In other words, can we be confident about the direction from A to B? Is it &ldquo;up,&rdquo; &ldquo;down&rdquo; or &ldquo;uncertain&rdquo;?
The third answer to this first question is that we are &ldquo;uncertain about the direction&rdquo; — it is not, and never should be, that we &ldquo;accept the null hypothesis.&rdquo;
